	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=838'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#9933CC;font-weight:bold; '>Iceblossom</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Guardian<br>
			
				Posts: 6566<br>
				
				Registered: 03-01-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=838'>







<img src="/eq/i/icons/Classes/shaman.gif" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=OT&message.id=8393#M8393">8</a> of 26
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 263 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<P>When you go to jury duty sometimes all you have to do is go... I've gone and sat in the "big room" for a day and never gone to a panel.&nbsp; When I lived in Alaska so many people showed up it was quite common for them to not use you.</P>
<P>When a jury is chosen (and different states and different types of trials have different numbers of jurors), they will select a number of potential jurors for the panel.&nbsp;&nbsp; This is usually done by a juror number (how you get that number differs from state to state).&nbsp; Say it is a fairly non-controversial case and they need a total of 8 for the panel (6 actual jurors and 2 alternates... but in my state you don't actually know who is a juror and who is an alternate until the final vote).&nbsp; They may call out 20 names/numbers.&nbsp; Last time I was a juror however, a big case came up (Mary Kay LeTournou was back in court, she is the former 2nd grade teacher who had an affair with a former student) and I think it was 100 or 200 potential jurors were called.</P>
<P>Then you go from the "big room" to the courtroom and that is where the jury selection is made for the final jury.&nbsp; Sometimes at that time a plea is entered or bargained and the jury is not needed (has happened to me).&nbsp; I got a "thanks for doing your part, you are free to go".</P>
<P>During the jury selection process you get another chance to plead hardship.&nbsp; Don't get smart though because some judges like to smack down people who deliberately try and get out of jury service, but a basic "I am a self employed store owner and am willing to do my part for a couple of days, but a trial longer than that would be a severe hardship and a very long trial would put me out of business" is more than enough for most.&nbsp; Generally you will be told the expected length of the trial.&nbsp; The lawyers don't really want people who don't want to be there either.&nbsp; Even if the judge does not except your hardship claim, you might be turned down by one or the other of the lawyers.&nbsp; They can turn you down for any reason or no reason at all.</P>
<P>So, with any luck maybe you will get a pretty easy/short trial like an auto accident of some sort or a theft case.&nbsp; Maybe you will go in and never serve.</P>
<P>From what I understand in my state, I blew the chance to get an easy trial by rescheduling.&nbsp; I was supposed to show up on a Monday, now I have to show up on Wednesday and the word is that is when the "hard' trial juries are chosen, the rapes and murders and long cases and such.&nbsp; But then again, maybe I won't even be selected for a jury pool.&nbsp; Or maybe I will be dismissed during the process.</P>
<P>I can say from the jury that I did participate in, I would have let that group of people judge me.&nbsp; We tried very hard to be good jurors, didn't talk about the case during breaks and such.&nbsp; Was a broad range of people from young to old, mixed races, mixed sexes, mixed incomes/jobs/retired.&nbsp; Oh, and the case where I was selected was a car accident civil case.&nbsp; The plaintiff claimed she was no longer able to work after the accident and wanted a cash settlement over the doctor and car bills handled by the defendents insurance.&nbsp; The defense put on a pretty good series of witnesses.&nbsp; I didn't make it through the trial as I said, but I think I was leaning towards not voting in her favor.&nbsp; When you make your decisions, the judge will give you instructions.&nbsp; In some states and cases you may only get to decide in favor or against (civil) or guilty or non-guilty (criminal).&nbsp; In other states and other cases you might get to decide on the level of charges, or the amount of the judgement.&nbsp; Some states for major crimes the same jury first decides guilt or innocence, and then there is a second period of court time and a second deliberation for the penalty.</P>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
		<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
		 <span class=date_text>05-04-2004</span> <span class=time_text>07:46 AM</span>
		</span>
		</td>

		
			<td colspan=2 class="msg_rating_cell" valign=bottom nowrap 
			
			>
			
				&nbsp;
				
				<br><br><a href="javascript:lipopup('/eq/notification?board.id=OT&message.id=8393&notification.type=1', 'notification', 600, 460, 'yes', 'yes')" class=text_smallest><u>Report Abuse to a Moderator</u></a>
				
		</td>
			
