	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=999'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#3366FF;font-weight:bold; '>Rawlden</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Lord<br>
			
				Posts: 10439<br>
				
				Registered: 03-01-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=999'>







<img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v607/Rawlden/storTrooper2.gif" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=OT&message.id=8409#M8409">10</a> of 26
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 246 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>Where I live, when you get&nbsp;called for jury duty, you are assigned to a "jury pool" for a term of 2 months. Each Friday you have to call the clerk's office to see if you need to show up on Monday. Mondays are when they select the juries for all the trials that are scheduled to start that week.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>On Monday, if you're told to be there, you go sit in the City Council chambers and they select groups of 20 at a time to go to the individual court rooms where juries are being selected.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I've been "called" twice in the last 30 years.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The first time I served on 2 different juries during my term. The last time I only had to go in on one Monday and was sent home within 2 hours without even getting into a court room.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>For the two cases I sat in for, one was a one day trial for check forgery and the other was a two week trial for price fixing in the local garbage hauling trade.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>In the first case, even though we all agreed that the accused was probably guilty, we aquitted him because the DA had pretty much botched the case and&nbsp;hadn't really proved anything "beyond a reasonable doubt". I think even the judge felt that the DA had screwed up because when he gave us our instructions he made a strong point about the "reasonable doubt" stuff.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The second case was much more interesting. I learned more than I ever wanted to know about the garbage hauling business. Local large waste hauling company and it's top two officers were charged with attempted price fixing with their smaller local competitors. The company president was not at the trail, he was hiding out of state, but the VP and the company itself were being tried in a joint trial. Two weeks of testimony and 2 days of deliberation. We convicted the company, but aquitted the VP. We pretty much decided that the absent company president was the guilty party and had skipped town to let the VP take the heat.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<font size="-2">Rawlden Gnomortis - Mage 56 - Tuesday Night Fight Club - Drinal<br>Rawlden Charlevoix - Enchanter 35 - Guardians of The Throne - Maelin Starpyre<br>/mourn <a href="http://icasualties.org/oif/" target="_blank">2680</a><br>"We will not be driven by fear into an age of unreason,<br> if we dig deep in our history and our doctrine, <br>and remember that we are not descended from fearful men" - Edward R Murrow</font>
							</div>
								
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
