<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Uumuuanu wrote:<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
LoveAMoose wrote:<BR>
<P>Interestingly enough, I am called at least once a year and immediately dismissed because I have a masters degree.</P>
<P>
<HR>

<P></P></BLOCKQUOTE>Wait,&nbsp; WTH does that have anything to do with it?&nbsp; GRRR<BR>
<DIV></DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV>Lawyers do not like well-educated people because they cannot be as easily manipulated as people who only have, say, a high school diploma.&nbsp; As the above poster stated, the higher the education, the more analytical that person will be.&nbsp; The last thing an attorney wants is someone in the jury room saying, "You know, if you look at the evidence from X angle, you can see how this guy is guilty/innocent."&nbsp; </FONT></DIV>
<DIV></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>It may not be fair, but attorneys are paid to do their best to represent their client(s), and jury selection is one of those functions.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
